  "primaryContentSections": [
    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The certificate, key, and trust services API is a collection of functions and data structures that you use to conduct secure and authenticated data transactions. Specifically, you use this API to manage and use:"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "unorderedList",
          "items": [
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "strong",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "Certificates and identities."
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " A certificate is a collection of data that identifies its owner in a tamper-evident way. When you use a certificate to distribute a public key, a receiver can be confident of its origin. You can also package a certificate together with its corresponding private key in an identity object that you keep secret."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "strong",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "Policies and trust services."
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " When you receive a certificate, before you can use the embedded public key, you have to answer the question, “Can I trust this certificate?” You conduct an evaluation of trust according to a set of criteria, or a trust policy."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "strong",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "Cryptographic keys."
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " After you have a key whose origin you trust, you can begin to conduct cryptographic operations, such as encryption or data signing and verification. These operations in turn typically serve a larger purpose, such as authenticating a user, transmitting data securely, or verifying that a block of data is unaltered since being sealed with a signature."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "aside",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "Rely on the classes of the "
                },
                {
                  "type": "reference",
                  "isActive": true,
                  "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/securityinterface"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": " framework to ensure a consistent experience when displaying certificates and trust settings to the user and when the user chooses among identities or modifies keychain settings. "
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "style": "note",
          "name": "Note"
        }
      ]
    }
